1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,000
https://slama.dev/comeback/

2
00:00:00,880 --> 00:00:01,920
Hi.

3
00:00:02,890 --> 00:00:03,510
Hi.

4
00:00:03,850 --> 00:00:04,610
Where were you?

5
00:00:04,610 --> 00:00:05,970
At the bank.

6
00:00:06,750 --> 00:00:08,230
And what put you in such a good mood there?

7
00:00:08,650 --> 00:00:10,650
Did you get a calendar and a candy again?

8
00:00:11,150 --> 00:00:12,750
That was my last time there.

9
00:00:13,450 --> 00:00:17,050
You say that every time, but usually you come back red as a lobster, yelling at the whole building.

10
00:00:17,450 --> 00:00:21,640
I must be reliable, because they let me manage my account from home.

11
00:00:21,640 --> 00:00:23,660
So where's this internet thing?

12
00:00:24,820 --> 00:00:25,440
Over there.

13
00:00:35,450 --> 00:00:37,890
So you set up online banking.

14
00:00:37,890 --> 00:00:39,170
You can't stop progress.

15
00:00:39,750 --> 00:00:43,290
So, www our bank dot...

16
00:00:43,290 --> 00:00:43,830
cz.

17
00:00:44,650 --> 00:00:48,690
And he didn't even want a microwave because he was afraid the waves would interfere with the radio.

18
00:00:48,690 --> 00:00:51,090
That was five years ago, I've come a long way since then.

19
00:00:51,650 --> 00:00:52,750
And here it is.

20
00:00:52,850 --> 00:00:53,650
Password.

21
00:00:54,150 --> 00:00:55,950
So what?

22
00:01:00,850 --> 00:01:02,250
That was my last time there.

23
00:01:05,150 --> 00:01:07,350
So you no longer think it can't be trusted?

24
00:01:07,450 --> 00:01:09,080
It's Vokolkova who can't be trusted.

25
00:01:09,250 --> 00:01:10,040
Who's Vokolkova?

26
00:01:10,040 --> 00:01:11,300
That old lady at the counter.

27
00:01:11,300 --> 00:01:13,150
Every time I come in, she laughs out loud.

28
00:01:13,650 --> 00:01:16,110
I suspect she's looking at my balance.

29
00:01:16,450 --> 00:01:18,510
Well she probably has to, when she's processing payments, right?

30
00:01:18,750 --> 00:01:20,430
But she's clearly showing it to the others.

31
00:01:20,430 --> 00:01:21,590
Last time they were all laughing.

32
00:01:24,250 --> 00:01:25,550
I wouldn't laugh.

33
00:01:25,550 --> 00:01:27,150
Let's not risk it.

34
00:01:30,450 --> 00:01:30,950
Alright.

35
00:01:34,090 --> 00:01:34,570
Wow.

36
00:01:35,620 --> 00:01:36,100
Wow.

37
00:01:36,100 --> 00:01:38,650
And now I can see everything.

38
00:01:38,850 --> 00:01:40,950
Perfectly organized, totally, look.

39
00:01:41,150 --> 00:01:43,380
Electricity, right, gas.

40
00:01:45,350 --> 00:01:52,950
I barely connect to the internet and already some Indians are stealing our money.

41
00:01:54,350 --> 00:01:54,850
I'll get you.

42
00:01:56,550 --> 00:01:57,410
That was a lamp.

43
00:02:27,750 --> 00:02:29,250
Someone's been draining our account for three years.

44
00:02:29,450 --> 00:02:30,790
Four hundred a month.

45
00:02:31,150 --> 00:02:32,810
That's probably some fee.

46
00:02:32,810 --> 00:02:34,650
Like a fee for cancelling a fee.

47
00:02:35,030 --> 00:02:36,330
Nonsense, not seventy crowns.

48
00:02:38,350 --> 00:02:39,250
Where are you going?

49
00:02:39,850 --> 00:02:41,650
Stay home, the family's in crisis.

50
00:02:41,850 --> 00:02:43,950
Father, it's just four hundred.

51
00:02:44,100 --> 00:02:45,440
Just four hundred?

52
00:02:45,480 --> 00:02:47,520
Do you know what you can get for four hundred?

53
00:02:47,740 --> 00:02:48,740
Nineteen and a half small rums.

54
00:02:48,960 --> 00:02:49,720
And what else?

55
00:02:50,250 --> 00:02:52,850
Someone's been systematically taking our money.

56
00:02:53,350 --> 00:02:55,950
I won't stand for this, I'm calling the police.

57
00:02:56,060 --> 00:02:58,080
Dad, please, don't bother over something so stupid.

58
00:02:58,300 --> 00:03:00,680
Fifteen thousand total, that's stupid to you?

59
00:03:00,960 --> 00:03:01,860
Damn, that was me.

60
00:03:02,750 --> 00:03:04,140
It's the money for the adoption.

61
00:03:04,250 --> 00:03:04,850
Ivuska, you had a baby?

62
00:03:07,050 --> 00:03:11,380
Uncle, please, a distance adoption. I adopted an Indian girl.

63
00:03:12,150 --> 00:03:13,250
Right, that makes sense.

64
00:03:13,680 --> 00:03:15,340
What, behind my back?

65
00:03:15,520 --> 00:03:17,520
How else? You'd never let me.

66
00:03:18,250 --> 00:03:19,750
How can you be so sure?

67
00:03:20,150 --> 00:03:25,450
When I was seven, I gave a blind man twenty crowns and you took fifteen back from his hat.

68
00:03:25,750 --> 00:03:28,050
Because I knew you'd want ice cream again.

69
00:03:30,450 --> 00:03:32,250
Seven hundred and fifty beers.

70
00:03:46,250 --> 00:03:51,950
Marcelka, apparently I can set it up so I get a text every time there's activity on the account.

71
00:03:52,850 --> 00:03:54,770
And where do you set that up?

72
00:03:55,170 --> 00:03:58,770
Payment order, standing order, or settings?

73
00:03:59,830 --> 00:04:00,350
Settings.

74
00:04:01,610 --> 00:04:02,130
Right.

75
00:04:05,350 --> 00:04:07,050
This is a whole new world.

76
00:04:08,750 --> 00:04:10,010
Hey, Marcelka, quick.

77
00:04:10,010 --> 00:04:16,450
Now a big blue table appeared and up here there's a little green frame.

78
00:04:17,150 --> 00:04:20,350
Tomas, how can I help you with that when I can't even look?

79
00:04:21,150 --> 00:04:23,150
Don't be upset, I'm sensitive about it.

80
00:04:23,350 --> 00:04:26,150
Vokolkova from the bank can confirm that.

81
00:04:30,250 --> 00:04:33,630
And I also need to cancel the standing payment order.

82
00:04:33,950 --> 00:04:35,750
You can't be serious about that?

83
00:04:35,950 --> 00:04:39,430
Nobody's going to spend family money without consulting the family first.

84
00:04:39,430 --> 00:04:40,410
Uncle, say something.

85
00:04:41,650 --> 00:04:43,250
Well I don't know, Ivuska, but...

86
00:04:43,850 --> 00:04:46,050
Seven hundred twenty beers, that's really a lot.

87
00:04:48,050 --> 00:04:51,700
Ivuska, these charities are one big scam.

88
00:04:51,850 --> 00:04:55,450
To be honest, I recently saw a very serious report about it on TV.

89
00:04:57,250 --> 00:04:58,350
I have photos of her.

90
00:05:04,050 --> 00:05:06,450
We're feeding that elephant too.

91
00:05:14,750 --> 00:05:19,450
Well, they really set you up nicely, girl, I'll give them that.

92
00:05:20,250 --> 00:05:21,450
I have letters from her.

93
00:05:23,650 --> 00:05:25,060
Nice scribbles.

94
00:05:25,850 --> 00:05:27,150
That's Hindi.

95
00:05:27,750 --> 00:05:28,550
Here's the translation.

96
00:05:30,350 --> 00:05:31,670
Tomas, it's a pittance.

97
00:05:31,850 --> 00:05:35,350
You know how much Zoran sends to those farmers in Afghanistan?

98
00:05:35,350 --> 00:05:36,070
Poor souls.

99
00:05:36,350 --> 00:05:38,650
Fields full of poppies and nothing to eat.

100
00:05:39,750 --> 00:05:41,290
And even if it weren't a scam.

101
00:05:41,330 --> 00:05:42,670
What do they need so much money for?

102
00:05:42,670 --> 00:05:44,050
Look, they have a water buffalo.

103
00:05:44,850 --> 00:05:45,990
The buffalo is for the fields.

104
00:05:46,150 --> 00:05:49,550
I'm sending them money so she can quit the fields and go study.

105
00:05:49,750 --> 00:05:51,050
For God's sake, Ivuska.

106
00:05:51,420 --> 00:05:54,160
The girl could have a great life and you're going to shove her into school?

107
00:05:54,580 --> 00:05:56,160
She's not doing that badly.

108
00:05:59,150 --> 00:06:01,110
What, she got a C in Hindi here?

109
00:06:01,250 --> 00:06:02,930
Do you know what a complex language that is?

110
00:06:02,930 --> 00:06:05,330
And maybe they have a different grading system, like in Russia.

111
00:06:05,490 --> 00:06:07,110
A C is a C everywhere.

112
00:06:07,570 --> 00:06:09,670
And she won the Punjabi Songbird.

113
00:06:09,810 --> 00:06:11,250
Maybe she'll make it as a singer.

114
00:06:11,430 --> 00:06:11,670
Yeah.

115
00:06:11,770 --> 00:06:13,590
You can brag about her to your friends.

116
00:06:13,670 --> 00:06:13,770
Yeah.

117
00:06:14,750 --> 00:06:15,750
What?

118
00:06:16,850 --> 00:06:18,250
There's a swear word here.

119
00:06:20,940 --> 00:06:21,720
Of course.

120
00:06:21,720 --> 00:06:22,940
A swear word.

121
00:06:22,950 --> 00:06:24,850
That's her name.

122
00:06:29,250 --> 00:06:29,770
Kundanika?

123
00:06:32,050 --> 00:06:33,850
In Hindi it means golden girl.

124
00:06:34,250 --> 00:06:36,950
I think I know which part means girl.

125
00:06:38,050 --> 00:06:38,780
Ozzak.

126
00:06:38,780 --> 00:06:42,120
For God's sake, Tomas, in India even gods are named like this.

127
00:06:42,240 --> 00:06:43,100
Like Kundalini.

128
00:06:43,220 --> 00:06:45,300
No one will talk like that in my apartment.

129
00:06:46,250 --> 00:06:50,150
So I'm supposed to brag about someone whose name I can't even say.

130
00:06:50,150 --> 00:06:51,070
Well I can.

131
00:06:52,150 --> 00:06:56,750
So I'll just cancel the standing payment order and Marcelka here will tell me how.

132
00:06:57,250 --> 00:07:01,950
So is it cancel standing order or in settings?

133
00:07:13,250 --> 00:07:19,850
I'd like to know what Iva was buying on March 21, 2008 at this shoe store for 520 crowns.

134
00:07:20,350 --> 00:07:21,150
Shoes?

135
00:07:23,450 --> 00:07:24,140
Just wondering.

136
00:07:24,350 --> 00:07:25,560
I can't trust her at all anymore.

137
00:07:25,950 --> 00:07:28,050
She's in hot water with me, she knows it, and she goes out.

138
00:07:28,280 --> 00:07:30,140
Well, she promised salmon for dinner.

139
00:07:30,380 --> 00:07:32,320
She knows I always soften up after salmon.

140
00:07:34,200 --> 00:07:34,680
Wait.

141
00:07:35,440 --> 00:07:35,920
Wait!

142
00:07:37,150 --> 00:07:39,550
There's some seventy crowns here every month.

143
00:07:39,680 --> 00:07:41,220
She has another child somewhere.

144
00:07:41,220 --> 00:07:45,150
No, that's the fee for being exempt from fees.

145
00:07:46,050 --> 00:07:47,390
And you pay that every month?

146
00:07:47,390 --> 00:07:47,510
Yeah.

147
00:07:48,050 --> 00:07:51,650
Tomas, I still don't understand why you're giving Ivuska such a hard time about this.

148
00:07:52,650 --> 00:07:58,200
She starts supporting some poorly studying girl with a vulgar name who might not even exist, with my money?

149
00:07:58,450 --> 00:07:59,650
What's next?

150
00:07:59,990 --> 00:08:03,870
Tomas, what's a pittance to you can change someone else's entire life.

151
00:08:04,050 --> 00:08:06,630
Zoran was in India and said the poverty there is terrible.

152
00:08:06,750 --> 00:08:10,150
When he saw that poor little boy shining his shoes, he almost cried.

153
00:08:11,750 --> 00:08:15,250
And how do I know that some guy isn't getting his shoes shined with my money...

154
00:08:15,450 --> 00:08:17,150
Give her another chance.

155
00:08:21,250 --> 00:08:25,950
I'd also like to know what Iva spent 150 crowns on at the fish shop.

156
00:08:44,050 --> 00:08:44,850
Who would have thought?

157
00:08:45,250 --> 00:08:45,950
Salmon.

158
00:08:46,850 --> 00:08:50,350
It looks like a cow with antlers but tastes like fish.

159
00:08:58,050 --> 00:09:02,650
Daddy, look how sadly she's looking at you.

160
00:09:06,950 --> 00:09:08,580
But we'll call her Dagmar.

161
00:09:16,750 --> 00:09:17,750
How did you choose her?

162
00:09:18,450 --> 00:09:20,580
I was looking for someone like me.

163
00:09:20,580 --> 00:09:21,580
In India?

164
00:09:22,750 --> 00:09:30,450
She's fourteen, her dad is a pain, she wants to leave home ASAP, and her best friend lives in the hut next door with a brother who's supposedly an idiot.

165
00:09:32,150 --> 00:09:33,150
It doesn't say that.

166
00:09:33,750 --> 00:09:34,850
But I'm describing it from here.

167
00:09:35,250 --> 00:09:38,340
In Hindi it translates to "boy who knows a pig."

168
00:09:38,340 --> 00:09:38,740
I see.

169
00:09:39,550 --> 00:09:41,200
And who's this weird guy?

170
00:09:41,350 --> 00:09:42,580
What weird guy?

171
00:09:42,850 --> 00:09:44,450
No, that's her uncle Rahul.

172
00:09:44,840 --> 00:09:45,240
Rahul?

173
00:09:46,350 --> 00:09:48,350
Now that's a name for a man.

174
00:09:49,050 --> 00:09:52,850
But that's a name a decent girl shouldn't have.

175
00:09:53,150 --> 00:09:54,920
Jesus, what's everyone's problem with it?

176
00:09:55,250 --> 00:09:57,040
What do you know about what Sasha means over there?

177
00:09:57,250 --> 00:09:58,250
Maybe it means ass.

178
00:09:58,700 --> 00:09:59,180
Lexa.

179
00:09:59,180 --> 00:10:02,550
Don't worry, maybe over there "ass" means Lexa.

180
00:10:03,650 --> 00:10:05,150
I'd be fine being called Ass.

181
00:10:05,650 --> 00:10:06,750
Ass Bucek.

182
00:10:07,250 --> 00:10:08,950
It's good to have a hook in your name.

183
00:10:10,350 --> 00:10:12,050
Lexa, but your real name is Alexandr.

184
00:10:13,350 --> 00:10:14,150
Come on.

185
00:10:16,950 --> 00:10:20,050
I'll write to her that my best friend's brother also "knows a pig."

186
00:10:20,750 --> 00:10:22,450
So she knows life is tough everywhere.

187
00:10:24,190 --> 00:10:24,670
Ass.

188
00:10:33,210 --> 00:10:35,330
She was first in the Punjabi Songbird.

189
00:10:35,550 --> 00:10:36,790
And she'll improve her Hindi.

190
00:10:37,150 --> 00:10:38,030
And what's her name?

191
00:10:38,030 --> 00:10:40,440
Did Ozzak say something?

192
00:10:41,000 --> 00:10:41,500
No.

193
00:10:43,750 --> 00:10:48,350
So, sirloin, small beer, Ozzak, thirteen hundred.

194
00:10:51,150 --> 00:10:53,650
Don't you think Ozzak's consumption is going up?

195
00:10:54,150 --> 00:10:55,160
What do you mean?

196
00:10:55,350 --> 00:10:56,450
I just have a feeling.

197
00:10:56,650 --> 00:10:58,550
Wait, that could be a problem.

198
00:10:58,850 --> 00:11:02,580
The boss built his entire business plan on Ozzak's consumption.

199
00:11:02,580 --> 00:11:03,480
What's that you've got?

200
00:11:04,960 --> 00:11:05,460
An Ozo-meter.

201
00:11:05,660 --> 00:11:06,160
What?

202
00:11:08,250 --> 00:11:12,450
For all I care, but based on this, he could run a brewery.

203
00:11:12,750 --> 00:11:14,480
Right, here's where Ivuska was born.

204
00:11:14,480 --> 00:11:16,840
Ah, and here he stopped singing in public.

205
00:11:16,840 --> 00:11:20,260
This is the ninety-nine dip, but otherwise perfectly stable.

206
00:11:20,450 --> 00:11:21,750
The boss got a loan based on it.

207
00:11:24,090 --> 00:11:24,630
Damn.

208
00:11:25,630 --> 00:11:26,730
What are you writing?

209
00:11:26,930 --> 00:11:27,710
I'm writing her a letter.

210
00:11:27,990 --> 00:11:29,750
To whom, that girl with the vulgar name?

211
00:11:30,670 --> 00:11:32,210
So Ozzak did say something.

212
00:11:33,650 --> 00:11:36,850
He was bragging and said he'd name his next band after her.

213
00:11:39,550 --> 00:11:43,950
Hey, what does a person have to do to set up an adoption like that?

214
00:11:44,550 --> 00:11:46,330
Don't tell me you want to adopt someone.

215
00:11:47,150 --> 00:11:48,350
I don't know, maybe I'd go for it.

216
00:11:48,650 --> 00:11:50,050
I don't even recognize you.

217
00:11:50,350 --> 00:11:54,250
Actually, I find it interesting that someone sends money for a child they'll never see.

218
00:11:54,450 --> 00:11:55,950
Isn't that called alimony?

219
00:11:57,250 --> 00:11:58,850
Explain that to my ex.

220
00:11:59,570 --> 00:12:00,050
Greetings.

221
00:12:00,710 --> 00:12:02,750
So far I can only do stamps and gluing.

222
00:12:02,930 --> 00:12:04,450
I haven't gotten to the greeting yet.

223
00:12:15,050 --> 00:12:16,420
I see you're writing to Dagmar.

224
00:12:16,420 --> 00:12:18,500
Do you know how to say investment savings?

225
00:12:18,500 --> 00:12:21,400
I'm writing to her about my online banking.

226
00:12:21,550 --> 00:12:23,100
No, but I know how to say miser.

227
00:12:23,100 --> 00:12:24,260
I'm writing to her about the same thing.

228
00:12:24,680 --> 00:12:25,300
Yeah, right.

229
00:12:26,550 --> 00:12:28,010
I've got it somewhat prepared.

230
00:12:28,350 --> 00:12:29,150
Listen.

231
00:12:30,550 --> 00:12:34,050
Dear girl, greetings from your adoptive grandpa.

232
00:12:34,650 --> 00:12:38,850
You should know that we don't exactly live in luxury either.

233
00:12:39,030 --> 00:12:43,670
I don't want to compare cultivating rice paddies with selling audio media.

234
00:12:43,870 --> 00:12:47,270
Both certainly have their bright and dark sides.

235
00:12:48,250 --> 00:12:50,450
Yeah, what's the bright side of cultivating fields?

236
00:12:51,250 --> 00:12:54,850
Pirates don't steal your rice and put it on the internet for free.

237
00:12:56,050 --> 00:12:59,280
We too turn every rupee in our hand three times.

238
00:12:59,280 --> 00:12:59,640
Dad.

239
00:13:00,540 --> 00:13:01,140
What?

240
00:13:02,250 --> 00:13:04,820
In the end she'll think we're millionaires and want more.

241
00:13:05,050 --> 00:13:08,050
She'll tell her friends, you know how many of them there are.

242
00:13:09,050 --> 00:13:10,310
Hi, this is Iva from Prague.

243
00:13:10,450 --> 00:13:14,750
I'm thinking our lives aren't that different, except for the water buffalo and your eleven sisters.

244
00:13:14,750 --> 00:13:16,010
She has eleven sisters?

245
00:13:16,450 --> 00:13:17,050
Well, they're called...

246
00:13:17,890 --> 00:13:18,750
I don't want to hear it.

247
00:13:20,950 --> 00:13:23,550
My best friend's brother also "knows a pig."

248
00:13:24,650 --> 00:13:27,150
And my father also sometimes "knows a pig."

249
00:13:28,150 --> 00:13:29,450
Wait, I don't understand that.

250
00:13:30,150 --> 00:13:32,040
That's just between us girls.

251
00:13:32,350 --> 00:13:32,850
Continue.

252
00:13:33,650 --> 00:13:35,260
Your uncle Rahul is a nice guy.

253
00:13:35,550 --> 00:13:40,250
Your dad shouldn't hassle him just because he hangs out by the monkey and chews betel.

254
00:13:42,750 --> 00:13:44,790
I sorted through some clothes at home.

255
00:13:45,350 --> 00:13:51,650
They're not exactly in style anymore, but maybe Dagmar can pull it off.

256
00:13:52,340 --> 00:13:52,940
What?

257
00:13:54,950 --> 00:13:58,850
Dagmar wants to graduate, not be a laughingstock.

258
00:13:58,980 --> 00:13:59,580
Ivuska.

259
00:14:00,250 --> 00:14:04,450
The eighties reached India just last year, so over there it's practically new.

260
00:14:07,950 --> 00:14:09,050
If you want to send something to that Indian girl with the dirty name.

261
00:14:09,050 --> 00:14:14,450
Bro, Indians live in America.

262
00:14:15,550 --> 00:14:17,850
Right, Indians in America.

263
00:14:19,920 --> 00:14:21,140
Send this too.

264
00:14:22,350 --> 00:14:25,140
But uncle, they don't drink beer in India.

265
00:14:25,350 --> 00:14:26,250
Exactly.

266
00:14:26,750 --> 00:14:29,050
I'll be like those who brought potatoes to America.

267
00:14:29,880 --> 00:14:30,440
To the Americans.

268
00:14:34,050 --> 00:14:36,050
Well that's nice of you, cutting back like that.

269
00:14:36,150 --> 00:14:36,750
See?

270
00:14:37,620 --> 00:14:39,080
I'll have to eat and drink carefully.

271
00:14:39,080 --> 00:14:41,320
But what wouldn't I do for the thirsty.

272
00:14:41,350 --> 00:14:44,450
She's fourteen and she already has a C in Hindi.

273
00:14:44,950 --> 00:14:46,160
Maybe she'll sing better.

274
00:14:46,160 --> 00:14:48,740
And anyway, we could go to India.

275
00:14:51,550 --> 00:14:56,450
I wrote her a letter too, but it's sealed, so nobody can read it.

276
00:15:02,750 --> 00:15:09,250
You're offering her three kilos if she writes that she started dating her best friend's brother and it was the best decision of her life?

277
00:15:10,750 --> 00:15:11,950
That kid's a stud.

278
00:15:12,450 --> 00:15:13,750
A regular Casanova.

279
00:15:14,950 --> 00:15:15,550
Casanova.

280
00:15:16,550 --> 00:15:25,150
It's been almost a month and she still hasn't written back.

281
00:15:25,550 --> 00:15:26,760
I think it's a scam.

282
00:15:27,050 --> 00:15:29,560
Absolutely not, then you couldn't trust anyone.

283
00:15:29,560 --> 00:15:30,260
Look at this.

284
00:15:31,450 --> 00:15:33,050
See that elephant?

285
00:15:33,450 --> 00:15:34,750
I think it's African.

286
00:15:35,450 --> 00:15:36,650
What if it's photoshopped?

287
00:15:36,650 --> 00:15:38,350
You'd know.

288
00:15:38,750 --> 00:15:39,650
I have an eye for it.

289
00:15:40,450 --> 00:15:41,150
Really?

290
00:15:42,450 --> 00:15:44,260
Then maybe I could confide in you.

291
00:15:44,260 --> 00:15:46,320
Look, this is Sasha in front of the Chanov housing estate.

292
00:15:46,480 --> 00:15:47,340
Looks legit.

293
00:15:48,460 --> 00:15:50,580
That's botched, like Lexa did it.

294
00:15:58,850 --> 00:15:59,350
I've got it.

295
00:16:01,550 --> 00:16:02,750
And it's translated.

296
00:16:03,660 --> 00:16:04,180
So.

297
00:16:06,250 --> 00:16:10,550
Dear Ivo, thank you for the nice letter and photos, but most of all for the gifts.

298
00:16:10,950 --> 00:16:14,950
The elephant Akesha needed a new bed, so any old rags will do.

299
00:16:18,250 --> 00:16:20,850
And the ginger drink I gave to Uncle Rahul.

300
00:16:21,150 --> 00:16:24,990
He said it's an interesting pastime and he'll send you something too.

301
00:16:25,350 --> 00:16:27,750
As soon as he finds the courage to cut back.

302
00:16:27,890 --> 00:16:29,370
You have a nice family.

303
00:16:29,370 --> 00:16:32,550
I especially like the kind dervish who lives with you.

304
00:16:32,850 --> 00:16:34,250
I think about him often.

305
00:16:36,750 --> 00:16:40,210
I just want to ask that you don't call me by that awful name.

306
00:16:40,550 --> 00:16:44,050
Where we live, only uncle uses that word when the buffalo butts him.

307
00:16:44,950 --> 00:16:46,850
What's wrong with the name Dagmar?

308
00:16:48,150 --> 00:16:49,070
I must go.

309
00:16:49,070 --> 00:16:51,890
Since our water buffalo got sick, we plow even at night.

310
00:16:52,150 --> 00:16:53,850
Things are really bad for us now.

311
00:16:54,030 --> 00:16:56,770
Dad even used the money he was saving for my dowry on medicine for it.

312
00:16:56,850 --> 00:16:59,950
Which is terrible, because everyone already says I'm an old maid.

313
00:17:02,360 --> 00:17:03,740
Hi, your Kund...

314
00:17:03,740 --> 00:17:04,160
Enough!

315
00:17:06,850 --> 00:17:07,810
Someone's thinking about me.

316
00:17:07,850 --> 00:17:10,450
Father, we should send them more money.

317
00:17:10,920 --> 00:17:12,000
That must be Simona.

318
00:17:12,000 --> 00:17:13,640
I don't know, Ivuska.

319
00:17:14,050 --> 00:17:16,150
What if this whole thing is a setup?

320
00:17:17,150 --> 00:17:18,850
She probably already poured me a beer.

321
00:17:26,750 --> 00:17:28,550
So you really weren't thinking about me?

322
00:17:28,550 --> 00:17:32,450
Sorry, in my free time I try to think about something nice.

323
00:17:32,950 --> 00:17:33,550
Damn.

324
00:17:35,550 --> 00:17:37,350
Ozzak, we're out of beer.

325
00:17:37,370 --> 00:17:37,890
What?

326
00:17:38,450 --> 00:17:39,450
Got you, right?

327
00:17:39,950 --> 00:17:42,680
I always say, a good scare is the best cure for hiccups.

328
00:17:43,750 --> 00:17:46,050
Simona, scare, not kill.

329
00:17:47,350 --> 00:17:49,250
Well then, also drink a liter of water.

330
00:17:49,550 --> 00:17:51,050
I said not kill.

331
00:17:57,350 --> 00:17:58,430
There's no point anymore.

332
00:17:58,850 --> 00:17:59,850
I'm going home.

333
00:18:01,150 --> 00:18:15,850
Greetings, Mr. Ozzak.

334
00:18:19,250 --> 00:18:19,850
Hey, Sasha.

335
00:18:20,580 --> 00:18:21,140
Hi, Ivo.

336
00:18:26,150 --> 00:18:28,550
And Ozzak has hiccups and can barely talk.

337
00:18:29,050 --> 00:18:32,850
I know a great cure for hiccups, but you have to cull the whole herd.

338
00:18:33,150 --> 00:18:34,390
Lexa, that's foot-and-mouth disease.

339
00:18:34,390 --> 00:18:34,910
Right.

340
00:18:36,850 --> 00:18:38,250
I already know who's behind this.

341
00:18:38,610 --> 00:18:39,650
So, Kundanika.

342
00:18:40,870 --> 00:18:41,250
Dagmar.

343
00:18:41,850 --> 00:18:42,850
Don't be vulgar.

344
00:18:43,130 --> 00:18:43,770
She's thinking about me.

345
00:18:43,970 --> 00:18:44,690
Bull.

346
00:18:45,310 --> 00:18:46,330
That's nonsense.

347
00:18:46,610 --> 00:18:47,250
It's not, bro.

348
00:18:47,750 --> 00:18:51,050
I asked everyone who might be thinking about me and Simona said no.

349
00:18:51,050 --> 00:18:51,830
You have to write to her.

350
00:18:51,950 --> 00:18:52,730
To make her stop.

351
00:18:52,950 --> 00:18:55,250
That'll be hard when her dad is sitting on the money over there.

352
00:18:56,190 --> 00:18:57,470
Ivuska, don't talk about me like that.

353
00:18:58,290 --> 00:18:59,710
The girl plows day and night.

354
00:18:59,710 --> 00:19:02,950
Their buffalo is dying, and you're hoarding a lousy four hundred.

355
00:19:03,850 --> 00:19:04,750
You have to write to her.

356
00:19:05,010 --> 00:19:05,910
Or I'll die.

357
00:19:05,910 --> 00:19:10,880
Well yeah, until dad pays for last month, the charity won't deliver any letters.

358
00:19:14,850 --> 00:19:17,700
Mr. Pacovsky, here are your baguettes and I'm running for the bus.

359
00:19:18,150 --> 00:19:20,050
It takes at least three hours to get to Chanov.

360
00:19:21,450 --> 00:19:22,650
The Ozo-meter is dropping.

361
00:19:23,750 --> 00:19:25,110
I'll probably have to set up a pub.

362
00:19:25,110 --> 00:19:26,730
Then every rupee will count.

363
00:19:29,950 --> 00:19:31,950
Fine, alright then.

364
00:19:40,350 --> 00:19:42,310
Well look at that, I thought it was a bank statement.

365
00:19:42,310 --> 00:19:42,670
It's not.

366
00:19:43,350 --> 00:19:44,950
Right, ok, thanks Marcelka.

367
00:19:45,550 --> 00:19:47,650
So I'll enter the payment order.

368
00:19:49,860 --> 00:19:50,420
Right.

369
00:19:50,420 --> 00:19:53,450
No, account number.

370
00:19:53,540 --> 00:19:55,680
Damn, why are the letters so small?

371
00:19:56,000 --> 00:19:57,100
You can enlarge it here.

372
00:19:57,200 --> 00:19:59,000
Respect the privacy zone.

373
00:20:05,050 --> 00:20:09,850
So four, zero, zero.

374
00:20:10,900 --> 00:20:11,620
Sorry.

375
00:20:12,550 --> 00:20:15,250
There, I'm done for today, right here.

376
00:20:15,550 --> 00:20:16,350
Zero, zero hellers.

377
00:20:18,550 --> 00:20:20,370
Careful not to send fifty extra.

378
00:20:22,450 --> 00:20:24,650
Send or cancel?

379
00:20:27,780 --> 00:20:28,500
Send.

380
00:20:29,350 --> 00:20:30,550
Ha, ha, ha.

381
00:20:31,150 --> 00:20:37,550
There, happy.

382
00:20:39,290 --> 00:20:41,530
Plowing a field would've been easier.

383
00:20:41,870 --> 00:20:43,570
And look, it works.

384
00:20:44,650 --> 00:20:47,140
Right, here it is, yes.

385
00:20:47,250 --> 00:20:48,750
Account number, one thousand.

386
00:20:55,250 --> 00:20:57,850
Oh God, I just sent forty thousand.

387
00:20:59,740 --> 00:21:00,660
They robbed me!

388
00:21:10,850 --> 00:21:13,050
Pacovsky, please, I have this problem, I...

389
00:21:15,650 --> 00:21:19,150
Hello, Pacovsky, I'd like...

390
00:21:21,850 --> 00:21:27,550
Hello, is there anyone alive, please?

391
00:21:27,790 --> 00:21:28,310
What?

392
00:21:28,450 --> 00:21:29,490
Oh, you're alive?

393
00:21:29,530 --> 00:21:30,050
You are, right?

394
00:21:30,050 --> 00:21:34,940
Great, please, Pacovsky here, I have a problem with your online banking.

395
00:21:34,940 --> 00:21:36,880
You see, I sent more money than I wanted to.

396
00:21:38,450 --> 00:21:39,750
Forty thousand, yes.

397
00:21:42,270 --> 00:21:44,050
No, don't look at my account.

398
00:21:44,270 --> 00:21:45,310
Just stop it somehow.

399
00:21:47,520 --> 00:21:49,040
Right, you can't do anything else, huh?

400
00:21:49,040 --> 00:21:53,080
Fine, fine, go ahead and look, but don't show anyone.

401
00:21:53,080 --> 00:21:54,160
God protect you.

402
00:21:54,950 --> 00:21:57,250
What do you mean it can't be stopped?

403
00:21:57,750 --> 00:21:59,240
Put me through to Mrs. Vokolkova.

404
00:21:59,450 --> 00:22:02,040
You know, that nice lady who's always laughing.

405
00:22:02,350 --> 00:22:03,550
She always helps me out.

406
00:22:05,890 --> 00:22:06,290
What?

407
00:22:06,430 --> 00:22:08,110
"Thank you for your time" too?

408
00:22:10,550 --> 00:22:11,350
Dad, calm down.

409
00:22:11,650 --> 00:22:14,150
If there's not enough money in there, it won't send anyway.

410
00:22:16,910 --> 00:22:17,390
Dad?

411
00:22:20,250 --> 00:22:21,650
Oh dear, oh dear.

412
00:22:35,250 --> 00:22:39,050
Hi, I was at the bank.

413
00:22:39,550 --> 00:22:41,550
I thought the last time was the last time.

414
00:22:41,750 --> 00:22:43,650
This time it really is the last.

415
00:22:43,930 --> 00:22:45,110
They closed our branch.

416
00:22:45,730 --> 00:22:47,770
They fired Vokolkova and all the others.

417
00:22:48,650 --> 00:22:50,500
They were looking at people's accounts.

418
00:22:50,750 --> 00:22:51,950
Now they'll be the ones laughing.

419
00:22:54,150 --> 00:22:58,650
Please, this came from India, you better open it, I might cry.

420
00:22:58,920 --> 00:23:00,180
They need it more than us.

421
00:23:00,380 --> 00:23:02,000
And I'll give out of love.

422
00:23:04,450 --> 00:23:07,290
What, is she at least sending rice?

423
00:23:07,650 --> 00:23:09,010
No, it's betel.

424
00:23:09,010 --> 00:23:10,270
For Uncle Ozzak.

425
00:23:10,410 --> 00:23:11,270
From Rahul.

426
00:23:11,850 --> 00:23:13,550
For God's sake, what is betel?

427
00:23:13,650 --> 00:23:15,210
Betel, I know that.

428
00:23:15,210 --> 00:23:16,770
Metla brought two sacks of it once.

429
00:23:16,910 --> 00:23:18,570
We chewed it all through ninety-nine.

430
00:23:21,460 --> 00:23:22,840
Well that's just great.

431
00:23:22,840 --> 00:23:25,250
Forty thousand for a handful of nuts.

432
00:23:25,450 --> 00:23:26,780
With that they'll cure the buffalo.

433
00:23:31,950 --> 00:23:33,550
And they cured our uncle?

434
00:23:37,650 --> 00:23:39,450
And they're not Indians.

435
00:23:52,650 --> 00:23:55,010
I have a feeling the money arrived.

436
00:24:01,150 --> 00:24:05,550
Maybe they'll be ungrateful and forget about us soon.

437
00:24:09,650 --> 00:24:13,320
Uncle, don't you want to go to the pub?

438
00:24:13,850 --> 00:24:15,150
Yeah, well, keep asking.

439
00:24:15,440 --> 00:24:16,000
I'm not going.
